<hw>Chat</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To talk of.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Chat
<hw>Chat</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Light, familiar talk;
conversation; gossip.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Snuff, or fan, supply each pause of <qex>chat</qex>,⟦br⟧
With singing, laughing, ogling, and all that.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A bird of the genus
<gen>Icteria</gen>, allied to the warblers, in America. The best known
species are the yellow-breasted chat (<spn>Icteria viridis</spn>), and
the long-tailed chat (<spn>Icteria longicauda</spn>). In Europe the name
is given to several birds of the family <fam>Saxicolid⟦ae⟧</fam>, as the
<stype>stonechat</stype>, and <stype>whinchat</stype>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bush chat</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Bush</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Chat
<hw>Chat</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A twig, cone, or little
branch. See <er>Chit</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>Small stones
with ore.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Chat potatoes</b></col>, <cd>small potatoes, such as are
given to swine.</cd> <mark>[Local.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chateau</ent>⟦br⟧
